T1  - The Propagation of Cyberattacks through the Financial System: Evidence from an Actual Event
AU  - KOTIDIS, ANTONIS
AU  - SCHREFT, STACEY L.
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13475
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 3313
EP  - 3358
VL  - 80
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13475
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT This article quantifies the effects of a multiday cyberattack that forced offline a technology service provider (TSP) to the banking sector. The attack impaired customers? ability to send payments through the TSP, but the business continuity plans of banks and the TSP reduced the effect by more than half. Large banks performed better. Through contagion, banks not directly exposed to the attack experienced a liquidity shortfall, causing them to borrow funds or tap reserves. The ability to send payments after hours helped avoid further contagion. These results highlight the importance of preparedness by the private and official sector for cyberattacks.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - ESG News, Future Cash Flows, and Firm Value
AU  - DERRIEN, FRANÇOIS
AU  - KRÜGER, PHILIPP
AU  - LANDIER, AUGUSTIN
AU  - YAO, TIANHAO
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13498
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 3499
EP  - 3554
VL  - 80
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13498
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT We investigate the expected consequences of negative environmental, social, and governance (ESG) news on firms' future profits. After learning about negative ESG news, analysts significantly downgrade their forecasts at short and longer horizons. Negative ESG news affects forecasts more strongly at longer horizons than other types of negative corporate news. The negative revisions of earnings forecasts following negative ESG news largely reflect expectations of lower future sales, rather than higher future costs. Quantitatively, forecast revisions can explain most of the negative impacts of ESG news on firm value. Analysts are correct to revise forecasts downward following negative ESG news.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Stock Market and Bank Risk-Taking
AU  - FALATO, ANTONIO
AU  - SCHARFSTEIN, DAVID
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13502
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 3223
EP  - 3261
VL  - 80
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13502
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT Using confidential supervisory risk ratings, we document that banks increase risk after going public compared to a control group of banks that filed to go public but withdrew their filings for plausibly exogenous reasons. The increase in risk improves short-term performance at the expense of long-term performance. We argue that the increase in risk stems from pressure to maximize short-term stock prices and earnings once the bank is publicly traded. After going public, banks owned by investors that place greater value on short-term performance increase risk more, and those managed by CEOs with more short-term compensation also increase risk more.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Anomalies and Their Short-Sale Costs
AU  - MURAVYEV, DMITRIY
AU  - PEARSON, NEIL D.
AU  - POLLET, JOSHUA M.
Y1  - 2025/12/01
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2025/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13501
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - J Finance
SP  - 3639
EP  - 3694
VL  - 80
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13501
Y2  - 2026/04/24
N2  - ABSTRACT Short-sale costs eliminate the abnormal returns on asset pricing anomaly portfolios. While many anomalies persist out-of-sample before accounting for short-sale costs, they cannot be exploited with long-short strategies due to stock borrow fees. Using a comprehensive sample of 162 anomalies, the average long-short portfolio return is a significant 0.14% per month before short-sale costs, and the returns are due to the short leg. However, the average is ?0.01% once returns are adjusted for borrow fees. Moreover, anomalies are not profitable even before fees if the high-fee observations, representing 12% of stock dates, are excluded from the analysis.
ER  - 

